Acanthopagrus latus, commonly known as the yellowfin seabream or gold-lined seabream, is a species of marine fish belonging to the family Sparidae. It is found in the Indo-Pacific region, ranging from the Red Sea and East Africa to Japan and northern Australia.

This species typically has a deep, laterally compressed body with a blunt, rounded snout. The dorsal fin has 11-12 spines and 12-14 soft rays, while the anal fin has 3 spines and 10-12 soft rays. The body is covered in ctenoid scales, and the coloration is typically golden-yellow or olive-green, with a yellowish-white belly.

Acanthopagrus latus is a demersal fish, inhabiting coastal waters, estuaries, and reef environments at depths ranging from 2 to 50 meters. It is an omnivorous species, feeding on a variety of small crustaceans, mollusks, and plant matter. This species is of commercial importance and is targeted by both commercial and recreational fisheries throughout its range.
